ce:section.ce:para:
The GCD analysis of 0.4CD-CF electrodes prepared at different carbonization temperatures was carried out at a fixed current density of 0.2 A g−1 in 6.0 M KOH electrolyte. The GCD curves of CF electrodes showed unsymmetric triangular shapes with a small IRdrop on each cycle (≅ 0.1 V), suggesting a high capacitive behavior of the EDLC electrode materials along with faradic current due to the presence of heteroatoms (Fig. 12a
                           ). The 0.4CD-C1200 electrode exhibited the longest time of charge-discharge cycle at a current density of 0.2 A g−1, indicative of the highest capacitive performance. As the current density increased, the charge-discharge cycle time of the 0.4CD-C1200 electrode (as an example) decreased, resulting in the reduction of Cs values as plotted in Fig. 12b and c. The calculated Cs from discharge curves demonstrated that the 0.4CD-C1200 electrode provided the highest Cs of ≅ 225 F g−1 at a current density of 0.2 A g−1. In addition, the Cs of this electrode was higher than that of other CF electrodes at all current densities, showing same trends with the estimated Cs results from CV curves. Electrochemical performances of the RWC-L/PAN CF electrodes, containing 0.4% w/v of CDs at various carbonization temperatures are displayed in Table 5
                           . The 0.4CD-C1200 electrode gave the best electrochemical performance with the maximum values of Cs (≅ 225 F g−1), ED (≅ 53 W h kg−1), and PD (≅ 130 W kg−1) at a current density of 0.2 A g−1. As expected, based on CF properties, the 0.4CD-C1400 electrode provided the lowest Cs (≅ 150 F g−1) and ED (≅ 35 W h kg−1) at same current density of 0.2 A g−1 and power density of ≅ 130 W kg−1.
